00:19:14.150 --> 00:19:17.720
was I initiated into adulthood?

00:19:17.720 --> 00:19:22.370
And if so, what comprised
that experience for me?

00:19:22.370 --> 00:19:28.130
So for me, that journey began
when I was nine years old.

00:19:28.130 --> 00:19:30.960
My dad died suddenly
of a heart attack,

00:19:30.960 --> 00:19:34.050
and I say goodbye to him,
goodnight to him, one day

00:19:34.050 --> 00:19:36.320
and he had a heart
attack in the night

00:19:36.320 --> 00:19:38.950
and I never saw him again.

00:19:38.950 --> 00:19:42.340
So not only did I
not have any closure

00:19:42.340 --> 00:19:46.620
with him, but on the
way to the funeral

00:19:46.620 --> 00:19:50.321
my uncle-- his younger brother--
he put his hand on my shoulder

00:19:50.321 --> 00:19:52.570
and he said, well Freddie,
you're the man of the house

00:19:52.570 --> 00:19:54.930
now.

00:19:54.930 --> 00:19:57.800
And I was nine.

00:19:57.800 --> 00:20:02.220
So the problem in that--
there's a lot of problems--

00:20:02.220 --> 00:20:07.240
but one of them is how exactly
am I supposed to do that?

00:20:07.240 --> 00:20:09.570
And I wanted desperately
as a nine-year-old

00:20:09.570 --> 00:20:12.320
to take care of my mother,
to take care of my older

00:20:12.320 --> 00:20:14.910
sister and my younger
brother, but I

00:20:14.910 --> 00:20:18.090
had no way of knowing
how to do that

00:20:18.090 --> 00:20:20.630
and how to grow into
that responsible man

00:20:20.630 --> 00:20:22.100
that I wanted to
be in my lifetime.

00:20:25.510 --> 00:20:28.440
And of course saying it
doesn't make it real, right?

00:20:28.440 --> 00:20:31.730
I needed initiation,
I needed education

00:20:31.730 --> 00:20:36.100
about becoming the man
that I wanted to become.

00:20:36.100 --> 00:20:40.970
So in my teen years, I got
way into drugs and alcohol

00:20:40.970 --> 00:20:44.360
and fortunately survived
it without hurting myself

00:20:44.360 --> 00:20:46.280
or anybody else.

00:20:46.280 --> 00:20:49.970
Which is a typical
experience for a lot

00:20:49.970 --> 00:20:52.640
of teens unconsciously--
in my view--

00:20:52.640 --> 00:20:55.530
seeking that experience
of initiation,

00:20:55.530 --> 00:20:57.800
wanting to push
themselves to the edge,

00:20:57.800 --> 00:21:00.740
but not having societal
mechanisms to hold

00:21:00.740 --> 00:21:03.830
them and keep them safe.

00:21:03.830 --> 00:21:09.200
So I never got that
mentorship, my uncle

00:21:09.200 --> 00:21:12.190
didn't stick around to
show me how to become

00:21:12.190 --> 00:21:13.430
that man that I wanted to be.

00:21:13.430 --> 00:21:16.320
I never got it from
many other men,

00:21:16.320 --> 00:21:17.570
they weren't there in my life.

00:21:20.320 --> 00:21:23.810
Fortunately, I did have--
starting in my late '20s--

00:21:23.810 --> 00:21:26.500
a mindfulness practice.

00:21:26.500 --> 00:21:31.500
And it started with Buddhism, as
I practiced Buddhism and I did

00:21:31.500 --> 00:21:35.030
a chanting practice,
and then it eventually

00:21:35.030 --> 00:21:38.720
lead to long meditation
retreats, a daily meditation

00:21:38.720 --> 00:21:43.890
practice, and now it's really
one of the fundamental pillars

00:21:43.890 --> 00:21:47.670
that holds up my life along
with so-called men's work

00:21:47.670 --> 00:21:49.040
and this rites of passage work.

00:21:49.040 --> 00:21:51.820
The two of them
together are really

00:21:51.820 --> 00:21:56.730
what sustain me in my lifetime.

00:21:56.730 --> 00:21:59.190
So you might be thinking
for yourself, well,

00:21:59.190 --> 00:22:01.700
what is it that sustains me?

00:22:01.700 --> 00:22:06.080
And what was, or did I
have a rite of passage?

00:22:06.080 --> 00:22:09.210
So for me, I finally
had it as I was

00:22:09.210 --> 00:22:11.340
approaching my 40th birthday.

00:22:11.340 --> 00:22:15.050
It was almost exactly
20 years ago in Chicago

00:22:15.050 --> 00:22:17.900
that I took a weekend workshop
with a group called The ManKind

00:22:17.900 --> 00:22:22.430
Project, a workshop called The
New Warrior Training Adventure.

00:22:22.430 --> 00:22:25.340
48 hours, you come at
5:00 PM on a Friday

00:22:25.340 --> 00:22:27.930
and leave at 5:00
PM on a Sunday.

00:22:27.930 --> 00:22:30.050
And I finally had
that experience

00:22:30.050 --> 00:22:35.250
that I so unconsciously
craved as a teen.

00:22:35.250 --> 00:22:39.190
And it taught me a number of
really fundamental things.

00:22:39.190 --> 00:22:41.530
It taught me about
accountability and integrity.

00:22:45.680 --> 00:22:48.490
As a young boy, I
intuitively knew

00:22:48.490 --> 00:22:52.810
I wanted to be a man
who could walk his talk,

00:22:52.810 --> 00:22:54.900
that when I said something
it was going to happen,

00:22:54.900 --> 00:22:57.310
and people could
rest assured in that.

00:22:57.310 --> 00:22:59.950
But I didn't know how
to make that happen,

00:22:59.950 --> 00:23:01.900
and I also didn't know
what to do in the case

00:23:01.900 --> 00:23:05.990
where I had to renegotiate
some agreement.

00:23:05.990 --> 00:23:09.270
So that's something that
I learned on that weekend,

00:23:09.270 --> 00:23:13.050
was about how to walk my talk,
how to be a man of integrity,

00:23:13.050 --> 00:23:15.500
and how to exercise
accountability

00:23:15.500 --> 00:23:18.710
in my ongoing daily life.

00:23:18.710 --> 00:23:21.800
Another thing it taught
me was about emotions,

00:23:21.800 --> 00:23:24.520
about how not to
fear my emotions

00:23:24.520 --> 00:23:27.460
or hide my emotions,
but actually how

00:23:27.460 --> 00:23:30.690
to learn to recognize
them and to integrate

00:23:30.690 --> 00:23:32.310
them effectively
and meaningfully

00:23:32.310 --> 00:23:34.040
in my ongoing life.

00:23:34.040 --> 00:23:37.690
And for most of us-- as men
especially in this culture--

00:23:37.690 --> 00:23:39.710
obviously that is
something we are not

00:23:39.710 --> 00:23:43.170
taught by the dominant
culture, right?

00:23:43.170 --> 00:23:46.260
If we're given any outlet
at all for our emotions,

00:23:46.260 --> 00:23:49.670
it's usually anger
and that's about it.

00:23:49.670 --> 00:23:52.180
So that was a
revelation for me--

00:23:52.180 --> 00:23:56.040
huge-- that I could actually
access some of these things

00:23:56.040 --> 00:24:00.130
like fear, like grief,
like anger, and use them

00:24:00.130 --> 00:24:03.790
as energizing tools to
live the life that I

00:24:03.790 --> 00:24:06.604
wanted to live as a man.

00:24:06.604 --> 00:24:08.020
The other thing
it taught me about

00:24:08.020 --> 00:24:11.300
was what we call shadows, which
is a neo-Jungian term-- Carl

00:24:11.300 --> 00:24:14.155
Jung, the Swiss philosopher
and psychologist.

00:24:16.860 --> 00:24:19.790
Shadows are the dark
side that's in all of us.

00:24:19.790 --> 00:24:22.580
Every human being has a
dark side, all of that

00:24:22.580 --> 00:24:26.810
that we hide, repress, and deny,
that we do not want to admit

00:24:26.810 --> 00:24:30.420
is true for the
beings that we are.

00:24:30.420 --> 00:24:34.880
So it took 50 strong men
on this weekend workshop

00:24:34.880 --> 00:24:38.540
to basically hold up a mirror
to me and say, take a look.

00:24:38.540 --> 00:24:43.270
This is you, too, and you need
to own these parts of yourself.

00:24:43.270 --> 00:24:46.710
And if you don't, you're
going to be dangerous.

00:24:46.710 --> 00:24:50.950
Because what happens is if
we don't acknowledge and own

00:24:50.950 --> 00:24:54.970
the shadows that are in each of
us, they'll leak out sideways.

00:24:54.970 --> 00:24:57.250
And before you know
it, we'll be beating up

00:24:57.250 --> 00:25:03.780
on children or domestic partners
or abusing ourselves, again,

00:25:03.780 --> 00:25:05.240
through drug and alcohol abuse.

00:25:05.240 --> 00:25:07.840
Whatever it looks like,
whatever form it takes,

00:25:07.840 --> 00:25:10.300
that shadow-driven
behavior comes

00:25:10.300 --> 00:25:13.770
from some fundamental
misunderstanding

00:25:13.770 --> 00:25:17.090
of who we are as human
beings-- a lie, if you will,

00:25:17.090 --> 00:25:19.000
that we took on
when we were young.

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:22.100
I'm not good enough,
I'm not worthy,

00:25:22.100 --> 00:25:26.500
I don't deserve success,
I don't deserve happiness.

00:25:26.500 --> 00:25:29.040
We all-- in a sense--
carry some of these lies.

00:25:31.590 --> 00:25:33.680
So the other thing-- a
number of other things

00:25:33.680 --> 00:25:35.138
that it taught me--
but one of them

00:25:35.138 --> 00:25:38.080
was how to live in a community
of men cooperatively rather

00:25:38.080 --> 00:25:39.720
than competitively.

00:25:39.720 --> 00:25:42.080
I had no idea that was possible.

00:25:42.080 --> 00:25:44.400
Being a child of this
dominant culture,

00:25:44.400 --> 00:25:47.140
I thought, well, men
are supposed to compete.

00:25:47.140 --> 00:25:50.950
They're supposed to compete for
scarce resources, jobs, money,

00:25:50.950 --> 00:25:52.520
women, whatever.

00:25:52.520 --> 00:25:55.280
To experience men
in that environment

00:25:55.280 --> 00:25:58.720
where I could actually see
and touch-- if you will--

00:25:58.720 --> 00:26:01.340
their open, vulnerable
hearts and have them do

00:26:01.340 --> 00:26:05.340
the same with mine, was huge.

00:26:05.340 --> 00:26:08.100
It also taught me a little bit
about my mission or my life

00:26:08.100 --> 00:26:09.350
purpose.

00:26:09.350 --> 00:26:11.910
And everybody has
one, in my belief,

00:26:11.910 --> 00:26:15.000
they just need to be
supported in finding it.

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:18.100
And that's something way
bigger than your job or even

00:26:18.100 --> 00:26:21.890
your career, it's fundamentally
what you're here on the planet

00:26:21.890 --> 00:26:26.280
to do, to accomplish
with your lifetime.

00:26:26.280 --> 00:26:29.380
And lastly, it taught me
how the meaning of life

00:26:29.380 --> 00:26:33.956
is to be found in service
and not in consumption.

00:26:33.956 --> 00:26:36.080
And that's, of course, the
dominant message, right?

00:26:36.080 --> 00:26:37.780
Despite what the
bumper sticker says--

00:26:37.780 --> 00:26:41.630
whoever dies with
the most toys wins--

00:26:41.630 --> 00:26:45.550
we're actually here to serve
and support each other.

00:26:45.550 --> 00:26:50.900
And the big
undelivered information

00:26:50.900 --> 00:26:53.230
from the dominant culture
is that's actually

00:26:53.230 --> 00:26:55.070
where happiness lies.

00:26:55.070 --> 00:26:58.310
That we'll actually be
happier as human beings

00:26:58.310 --> 00:27:02.520
if we can see the impact of
our actions on those around us

00:27:02.520 --> 00:27:05.760
and how it's making
their lives better.

00:27:05.760 --> 00:27:08.670
So that's where I first
learned that lesson.

00:27:08.670 --> 00:27:11.760
So those are just some of the
lessons that rites of passage

00:27:11.760 --> 00:27:13.650
teaches.

00:27:13.650 --> 00:27:16.610
Now you just saw this
definition in the movie,

00:27:16.610 --> 00:27:18.620
so I'm not going to spend
a lot of time on it,

00:27:18.620 --> 00:27:23.040
but I just want to go back over
a couple of key parts of it.

00:27:23.040 --> 00:27:25.210
So you know the
old maxim is true,

00:27:25.210 --> 00:27:27.650
that it takes a whole
village to raise a child.

00:27:27.650 --> 00:27:30.960
Parents can't do it alone.

00:27:30.960 --> 00:27:34.950
And doing so-- reaching out
as a parent to a neighbor

00:27:34.950 --> 00:27:40.480
or to a coach or to a teacher
or a friend of the family--

00:27:40.480 --> 00:27:45.390
actually helps rebuild this torn
and broken fabric of community

00:27:45.390 --> 00:27:48.370
that we all suffer from
in this modern world.

00:27:48.370 --> 00:27:52.360
Broken and torn communities.

00:27:52.360 --> 00:27:54.760
So that's one key thing.

00:27:54.760 --> 00:27:58.480
The other is perceived to
be transformative by youth.

00:27:58.480 --> 00:28:03.470
It's not for us as adults
to say, OK, you've arrived,

00:28:03.470 --> 00:28:06.910
you're a young adult now, you're
a man now, you're a woman now.

00:28:06.910 --> 00:28:10.660
We need to have
them evidence this,

00:28:10.660 --> 00:28:13.595
and they don't do it through
language by and large,

00:28:13.595 --> 00:28:14.720
although that's part of it.

00:28:14.720 --> 00:28:17.950
They say wow, I
can't believe what

00:28:17.950 --> 00:28:21.850
I've just experienced but man,
I am a different human being.

00:28:21.850 --> 00:28:26.240
That's great, but we need
to see it in their eyes.

00:28:26.240 --> 00:28:27.690
Alive.

00:28:27.690 --> 00:28:29.631
We need to see it in
their body movements.

00:28:29.631 --> 00:28:31.880
There's some excitement,
there's some aliveness there,

00:28:31.880 --> 00:28:36.010
and some groundedness
there, too.

00:28:36.010 --> 00:28:40.800
So the other thing is
offer increased status.

00:28:40.800 --> 00:28:44.160
They need to know
that they've arrived,

00:28:44.160 --> 00:28:47.300
they're equals now
with us as adults.

00:28:47.300 --> 00:28:52.480
And voting, drinking, driving,
having sex, they're not enough.

00:28:52.480 --> 00:28:56.580
We need to ritually consecrate
these moments in time,

00:28:56.580 --> 00:28:58.780
and ideally come
together as community

00:28:58.780 --> 00:29:03.770
to celebrate and acknowledge the
learnings, the education that

00:29:03.770 --> 00:29:07.670
has preceded it, that has
justified this moment where

00:29:07.670 --> 00:29:11.250
we can celebrate these young
people for this passage.

00:29:11.250 --> 00:29:13.760
It's fundamental.

00:29:13.760 --> 00:29:17.160
So there's three main stages,
really, of rites of passage.

00:29:17.160 --> 00:29:19.440
And this all comes
from Arnold van Gennep,

00:29:19.440 --> 00:29:22.360
who wrote about this
over 100 years ago.

00:29:22.360 --> 00:29:25.160
Separation or descent
is really one.

00:29:25.160 --> 00:29:30.780
We have to separate young
people from everything

00:29:30.780 --> 00:29:32.700
that is familiar to
them and yes, that

00:29:32.700 --> 00:29:35.990
includes computers and
cell phones and TVs

00:29:35.990 --> 00:29:37.670
and all the rest of it.

00:29:37.670 --> 00:29:39.930
We have to separate
them from the patterns

00:29:39.930 --> 00:29:42.550
that establish their
daily life-- sleep,

00:29:42.550 --> 00:29:44.165
food, maybe even dress.

00:29:47.280 --> 00:29:50.320
And it's also called descent
because it's dropping.

00:29:50.320 --> 00:29:52.930
It's dropping into what
we are fundamentally

00:29:52.930 --> 00:29:55.680
as human beings, that
all of that other stuff--

00:29:55.680 --> 00:30:00.010
the trappings of daily
modern life-- obfuscate,

00:30:00.010 --> 00:30:03.320
cloud, make difficult to see.

00:30:03.320 --> 00:30:07.130
So then the key part--
the ordeal or threshold--

00:30:07.130 --> 00:30:09.990
it's also called
liminality, that word

00:30:09.990 --> 00:30:14.640
that means sort of Twilight
Zone between the worlds.

00:30:14.640 --> 00:30:17.810
So there has to be
some kind of ordeal

00:30:17.810 --> 00:30:23.360
where the young person is
challenged-- physically,

00:30:23.360 --> 00:30:26.530
mentally, spiritually,
emotionally.

00:30:26.530 --> 00:30:30.110
They're brought down into
the depths of their being

00:30:30.110 --> 00:30:33.030
and they can experience--
at a fundamental level--

00:30:33.030 --> 00:30:37.555
just how actually resilient
they are, how strong they are.

00:30:37.555 --> 00:30:39.305
They won't know this
until they're tested.

00:30:42.160 --> 00:30:45.190
And then the reintegration or
homecoming, as it's called.

00:30:45.190 --> 00:30:48.020
So you have to come back
from this experience,

00:30:48.020 --> 00:30:50.180
you have to be-- again--
ritually welcomed,

00:30:50.180 --> 00:30:53.430
celebrated by your
community and family,

00:30:53.430 --> 00:30:56.970
and you have to be
reintegrated so that what's key

00:30:56.970 --> 00:31:00.530
here is the learning, the
learning about who you

00:31:00.530 --> 00:31:05.000
are as a unique individual,
the gifts that you have.

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:07.090
The elders, ideally,
will help you

00:31:07.090 --> 00:31:08.700
understand what
those gifts are so

00:31:08.700 --> 00:31:10.710
that you can integrate
them into the community

00:31:10.710 --> 00:31:13.470
and start to give them freely.

00:31:13.470 --> 00:31:18.730
Because a gift ungiven is a
gift that almost doesn't exist.

00:31:18.730 --> 00:31:22.630
It has to be given
to those around.

00:31:22.630 --> 00:31:25.230
So what does this look
like for an average teen?

00:31:25.230 --> 00:31:29.410
Well, adolescents have to
confront two base fears.

00:31:29.410 --> 00:31:33.190
One is leaving
mom and dad, home.

00:31:33.190 --> 00:31:35.670
No one wants to do
that, why should you?

00:31:35.670 --> 00:31:37.680
You get three meals
a day, ideally, you

00:31:37.680 --> 00:31:40.220
have a roof over your
head, you're taken care of.

00:31:40.220 --> 00:31:43.050
You have to be-- in
a sense-- forced away

00:31:43.050 --> 00:31:46.000
from that relationship.

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:49.900
Some writers on
this subject matter

00:31:49.900 --> 00:31:53.650
call it cutting that
second umbilical cord.

00:31:53.650 --> 00:31:55.460
That second umbilical
cord, the one

00:31:55.460 --> 00:31:57.180
that happens at the
end of adolescence.

00:31:57.180 --> 00:32:03.240
That has to be cut and it's
not happening now in society.

00:32:03.240 --> 00:32:05.190
We'll return to that subject.

00:32:05.190 --> 00:32:08.540
So the other thing, there
has to be-- at some level--

00:32:08.540 --> 00:32:10.900
a facing of death.

00:32:10.900 --> 00:32:15.450
And the simple truth is it's
bad enough, challenging enough--

00:32:15.450 --> 00:32:17.450
and some of you, I'm sure,
have experienced this

00:32:17.450 --> 00:32:20.020
like I have one-- when somebody
close to you in your family,

00:32:20.020 --> 00:32:23.010
somebody dear to you has died.

00:32:23.010 --> 00:32:26.480
That, in a sense, can be a
beginning of a rite of passage.

00:32:26.480 --> 00:32:29.260
If you have the proper
mentorship from an elder,

00:32:29.260 --> 00:32:30.900
they can help you
understand what

00:32:30.900 --> 00:32:34.650
is the meaning of this moment
in time in your lifetime?

00:32:34.650 --> 00:32:37.230
I didn't have that when I was
nine years old, from my uncle

00:32:37.230 --> 00:32:39.500
or anybody else.

00:32:39.500 --> 00:32:41.940
But even more than that,
we have to understand

00:32:41.940 --> 00:32:46.250
our own mortality,
the fragility and yet

00:32:46.250 --> 00:32:48.920
the preciousness of
this very sacred thing

00:32:48.920 --> 00:32:51.180
of our own human life.

00:32:51.180 --> 00:32:54.650
And until we're brought
into proximity with death,

00:32:54.650 --> 00:32:57.640
until we at least fear
that we're going to die,

00:32:57.640 --> 00:32:59.710
we're not going to
experience that.

00:32:59.710 --> 00:33:02.210
It's not going to happen.

00:33:02.210 --> 00:33:04.570
We'll unconsciously fear
it the rest of our lives,

00:33:04.570 --> 00:33:07.150
but we won't know in
our hearts and souls

00:33:07.150 --> 00:33:10.970
what our capacity is
to withstand challenges

00:33:10.970 --> 00:33:14.240
and to face death.

00:33:14.240 --> 00:33:20.170
So the ordeal-- in a sense,
what's called for here

00:33:20.170 --> 00:33:22.920
is the young person
needs to metaphorically

00:33:22.920 --> 00:33:29.750
die to their childhood self
to be reborn as an adult.

00:33:29.750 --> 00:33:33.210
And then the reintegration--
one of the key lessons that's

00:33:33.210 --> 00:33:36.170
a part of rite of passage
that needs to be brought back

00:33:36.170 --> 00:33:40.140
into community is every
child and every adolescent

00:33:40.140 --> 00:33:45.380
tends to see the world in
a me, me, me kind of way.

00:33:45.380 --> 00:33:47.730
And to be a
fully-mature adult, it

00:33:47.730 --> 00:33:52.570
requires us to see
things as us, us, us.

00:33:52.570 --> 00:33:55.570
We need to do it
together, because

00:33:55.570 --> 00:33:57.965
without that cooperation,
there is only domination.

00:34:01.880 --> 00:34:04.470
So there's lots of different
forms of rites of passage

00:34:04.470 --> 00:34:05.970
that still exist
around the world,

00:34:05.970 --> 00:34:07.290
these are just some of them.

00:34:13.600 --> 00:34:17.330
And it's interesting
because all of the damage

00:34:17.330 --> 00:34:20.139
that we've done to
indigenous cultures

00:34:20.139 --> 00:34:23.070
around the world who have
understood for thousands

00:34:23.070 --> 00:34:25.692
of years-- the African
proverb that you saw

00:34:25.692 --> 00:34:26.900
at the beginning of the film.

00:34:26.900 --> 00:34:28.719
"If we do not
initiate the young,

00:34:28.719 --> 00:34:32.889
they will burn down the
village to feel the heat."

00:34:32.889 --> 00:34:34.820
It's a beautiful proverb.

00:34:34.820 --> 00:34:37.770
Indigenous cultures-- in their
own way across the globe--

00:34:37.770 --> 00:34:42.639
have understood this,
have understood this.

00:34:42.639 --> 00:34:52.420
So it's interesting because some
of what has survived in time

00:34:52.420 --> 00:34:57.130
are some of these ceremonies,
some of these processes.

00:34:57.130 --> 00:35:01.070
But I'm curious, are any of
you Jewish out there like I am?

00:35:01.070 --> 00:35:04.020
OK, I don't know
about you, but when

00:35:04.020 --> 00:35:06.340
it was my friends'
time for bar mitzvah

00:35:06.340 --> 00:35:07.930
there was one
question that came up.

00:35:07.930 --> 00:35:10.550
What did you get?

00:35:10.550 --> 00:35:11.830
What did you get?

00:35:11.830 --> 00:35:14.810
It was not, how are
you transformed?

00:35:14.810 --> 00:35:16.010
Are you a different being?

00:35:16.010 --> 00:35:19.720
Do you feel like a man now?

00:35:19.720 --> 00:35:21.700
And that's just
an example of how

00:35:21.700 --> 00:35:26.040
so many of these processes that
still have survived to this day

00:35:26.040 --> 00:35:29.190
have been co-opted
by consumer culture,

00:35:29.190 --> 00:35:31.890
and they've lost that
essential potency

00:35:31.890 --> 00:35:35.120
that's required to drive
transformation and make

00:35:35.120 --> 00:35:37.210
it happen.

00:35:37.210 --> 00:35:40.430
There's a couple of other
key fundamental lessons--

00:35:40.430 --> 00:35:45.050
in my experience-- that result
as a process of healthy rite

00:35:45.050 --> 00:35:47.350
of passage or initiation.

00:35:47.350 --> 00:35:50.770
Knowing your place in the
cosmos is one of them.

00:35:50.770 --> 00:35:53.790
There's a fundamental
paradox that's

00:35:53.790 --> 00:35:57.700
I think at the essence of
every human life, and that is--

00:35:57.700 --> 00:35:59.800
and I was reminded of that
a couple days ago when

00:35:59.800 --> 00:36:03.420
I was watching the beautiful
blood moon in the eclipse,

00:36:03.420 --> 00:36:05.930
I don't know if any
of you saw that-- how

00:36:05.930 --> 00:36:09.990
small and insignificant
we are at one level,

00:36:09.990 --> 00:36:13.740
in the greater
scheme of the cosmos.

00:36:13.740 --> 00:36:17.420
We are specks of dust.

00:36:17.420 --> 00:36:20.210
But the other half of
that paradoxical equation

00:36:20.210 --> 00:36:23.620
is that each of us is
immeasurably powerful.

00:36:23.620 --> 00:36:27.790
Immeasurably, and that there's
literally no limit to what

00:36:27.790 --> 00:36:31.720
we can manifest and how
we can impact and change

00:36:31.720 --> 00:36:34.210
the lives of those around us.

00:36:34.210 --> 00:36:38.070
So holding that paradox-- and
in fact experiencing it almost

00:36:38.070 --> 00:36:41.310
in the bodily way--
is a fundamental part

00:36:41.310 --> 00:36:43.930
of a healthy rite of passage.

00:36:43.930 --> 00:36:46.140
So knowing that you're
part of the web of life

00:36:46.140 --> 00:36:48.070
is also a part of that.

00:36:48.070 --> 00:36:53.370
That you don't exist apart from
trees and rocks and waters.

00:36:53.370 --> 00:36:55.460
We don't exist.

00:36:55.460 --> 00:36:57.230
Knowing your mission
or life purpose.

00:36:57.230 --> 00:36:58.560
I already spoke to that.

00:36:58.560 --> 00:37:02.600
Another way of saying that,
again, is gifts or medicine.

00:37:02.600 --> 00:37:04.730
Beautiful terms.

00:37:04.730 --> 00:37:08.010
Knowing the depths of your
physical and mental capacities.

00:37:08.010 --> 00:37:11.376
Again, I think that's part of
why young people put themselves

00:37:11.376 --> 00:37:12.000
through trials.

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:14.280
Well, let's see if we
can drink, let's see

00:37:14.280 --> 00:37:18.510
if we can drink three
cases in about 10 minutes.

00:37:18.510 --> 00:37:22.110
Unconsciously, I think that
part of the drive toward that

00:37:22.110 --> 00:37:25.730
is seeing, what is the
limit of this physical body?

00:37:30.240 --> 00:37:34.110
Emotions and how to handle them.

00:37:34.110 --> 00:37:37.120
I just myself did
another rite of passage--

00:37:37.120 --> 00:37:38.880
if you will-- a
Vision Quest, and I

00:37:38.880 --> 00:37:41.490
spent four days up
in the Eastern Sierra

00:37:41.490 --> 00:37:47.380
at about 10,000 feet in a
mountain desert fasting.

00:37:47.380 --> 00:37:51.580
It was about 100 degrees
every day, and believe me,

00:37:51.580 --> 00:37:54.250
all kinds of emotions came up.

00:37:54.250 --> 00:37:56.490
So it gave me an
opportunity again

00:37:56.490 --> 00:38:02.090
to look at fear, to look a grief
that surfaced as I recollected

00:38:02.090 --> 00:38:07.770
and thought back on mistakes
that I've made in my lifetime,

00:38:07.770 --> 00:38:11.430
to look at all of my
emotions and to reintegrate

00:38:11.430 --> 00:38:15.510
them and understand
them and not fear them.

00:38:15.510 --> 00:38:17.150
Again, service to community.

00:38:17.150 --> 00:38:22.430
That's an essential component,
as well as self-empowerment.

00:38:22.430 --> 00:38:27.450
So imagine-- if you will--
that we live in a society

00:38:27.450 --> 00:38:31.566
where all teens have a deep
sense of purpose for their life

00:38:31.566 --> 00:38:33.565
and they're connected to
their deepest passions.

00:38:36.250 --> 00:38:40.720
Imagine that we live in a
world where all teens know

00:38:40.720 --> 00:38:43.430
their physical, mental,
spiritual, and emotional limit,

00:38:43.430 --> 00:38:48.130
so they don't have to seek them
through unconscious trials.

00:38:48.130 --> 00:38:51.280
And imagine all teens know the
rights and responsibilities

00:38:51.280 --> 00:38:54.430
of adulthood, and feel
welcome and accepted

00:38:54.430 --> 00:38:58.860
by elders, by older adults.

00:38:58.860 --> 00:39:01.410
And imagine that they're
actually stakeholders

00:39:01.410 --> 00:39:03.510
in their community,
deeply invested

00:39:03.510 --> 00:39:06.110
in a community that's thriving.

00:39:06.110 --> 00:39:08.690
I think that's part of the
reason I live in Oakland,

00:39:08.690 --> 00:39:10.880
and I think that's part of
the reason why we have so

00:39:10.880 --> 00:39:13.000
many disaffected young people.

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:16.550
Nobody's coming up to
them saying, I see you,

00:39:16.550 --> 00:39:19.610
I see the brilliance that you
carry, I see some of the gifts

00:39:19.610 --> 00:39:20.520
that you have.

00:39:20.520 --> 00:39:23.500
Please offer them, bring
them into our community,

00:39:23.500 --> 00:39:25.810
you are a stakeholder here.

00:39:25.810 --> 00:39:30.120
And give them the room
to start to manifest

00:39:30.120 --> 00:39:31.680
some of that brilliance.

00:39:31.680 --> 00:39:34.630
We don't do it.

00:39:34.630 --> 00:39:37.040
So imagine, too,
that all parents

00:39:37.040 --> 00:39:41.610
know when it's their time to
let their young people go forth

00:39:41.610 --> 00:39:44.790
on their own.

00:39:44.790 --> 00:39:47.700
This is a problem,
like I said before.

00:39:47.700 --> 00:39:51.900
And yes, I get it, it's
partly an economic issue.

00:39:51.900 --> 00:39:54.630
It's really, really
tough now for most people

00:39:54.630 --> 00:39:59.830
in their '20s to get good jobs,
to find decent-paying work.

00:39:59.830 --> 00:40:02.170
And it's especially tough--
interestingly enough--

00:40:02.170 --> 00:40:05.430
for boys, for young men,
at an almost two to one

00:40:05.430 --> 00:40:08.200
ratio to women.

00:40:08.200 --> 00:40:16.110
But in addition to that, there's
no dominant cultural support

00:40:16.110 --> 00:40:20.190
for parents to say, you have
got to turn your young person

00:40:20.190 --> 00:40:20.870
loose.

00:40:20.870 --> 00:40:23.300
Otherwise, they won't
manifest their own greatness,

00:40:23.300 --> 00:40:27.040
they won't reach their
potential as human beings.

00:40:27.040 --> 00:40:29.917
I gave a talk about a year
ago in North Carolina,

00:40:29.917 --> 00:40:32.000
and there was a woman who
came up to me afterward.

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:34.860
She said, I'm so glad to
hear your talk because I

00:40:34.860 --> 00:40:38.720
kick my kids of the
house at 18 and I just

00:40:38.720 --> 00:40:41.460
felt like they really needed it.

00:40:41.460 --> 00:40:46.320
And my point is not to condone
or condemn-- I don't know her

00:40:46.320 --> 00:40:48.502
and I don't know her
kids or her situation,

00:40:48.502 --> 00:40:50.710
whether it was the right
choice of the wrong choice--

00:40:50.710 --> 00:40:54.700
but what I do know is there's
no cultural support for her.

00:40:54.700 --> 00:40:56.330
There's no community
support for her

00:40:56.330 --> 00:40:59.560
in making that choice,
in affirming that choice

00:40:59.560 --> 00:41:01.200
or saying no, maybe
it's too early,

00:41:01.200 --> 00:41:02.835
maybe they need
another couple years.

00:41:06.350 --> 00:41:09.720
And lastly, imagine no
more suspended adolescents

00:41:09.720 --> 00:41:11.720
running the country.

00:41:11.720 --> 00:41:13.180
How sweet would that be?

00:41:16.730 --> 00:41:18.200
It's interesting
because it makes

00:41:18.200 --> 00:41:21.310
me reflect on John Boehner
and his stepping down

00:41:21.310 --> 00:41:23.770
from Animal House.

00:41:23.770 --> 00:41:29.850
I actually think that was
a very moral, and in fact,

00:41:29.850 --> 00:41:33.910
and noble decision
on his part to make.

00:41:33.910 --> 00:41:37.430
And I saw it as a
real culmination

00:41:37.430 --> 00:41:39.590
in a way of his own
rite of passage,

00:41:39.590 --> 00:41:42.150
in trying to run herd over
this thing called Congress

00:41:42.150 --> 00:41:44.342
over the last few
years where so many

00:41:44.342 --> 00:41:46.800
of the members of his own party
are giving him the greatest

00:41:46.800 --> 00:41:47.790
grief.

00:41:47.790 --> 00:41:52.940
He's like, no, enough, I'm
going to step away from this.

00:41:52.940 --> 00:41:58.050
We could go into that, but I
don't have time for it now.

00:41:58.050 --> 00:42:01.010
So ultimately, young
people have to find a way

00:42:01.010 --> 00:42:04.550
to live their dreams,
heal their spirits,

00:42:04.550 --> 00:42:07.652
and to change the world.

00:42:07.652 --> 00:42:09.360
We need to give them
those opportunities.

00:42:11.900 --> 00:42:16.820
This I won't go into, this
is some of what we're doing.

00:42:16.820 --> 00:42:20.160
As I said, I'm about
art and service,

00:42:20.160 --> 00:42:26.600
I am not the ideal selected
guy to head a social movement.

00:42:26.600 --> 00:42:28.410
And yet that's
what I found myself

00:42:28.410 --> 00:42:31.180
doing because I didn't
see anybody else doing it.

00:42:31.180 --> 00:42:35.360
And I thought, this is
essential, we have to do this.

00:42:35.360 --> 00:42:37.110
So these are some of
the things that we've

00:42:37.110 --> 00:42:39.460
been doing over
the last few years

00:42:39.460 --> 00:42:42.980
to really try to reawaken
the adults of this world

00:42:42.980 --> 00:42:47.520
to their responsibilities
to young people.

00:42:47.520 --> 00:42:50.140
So let me share one
last film with you

00:42:50.140 --> 00:42:53.270
and then I'll close here.

00:42:53.270 --> 00:42:59.790
So this is the voices of
the young people speaking

00:42:59.790 --> 00:43:03.234
for themselves about what
it is that they need.

00:43:03.234 --> 00:43:04.710
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:43:04.710 --> 00:43:08.270
-There's so much struggle that
our kids are going through.

00:43:08.270 --> 00:43:10.454
-Kids don't have
the attention, even

00:43:10.454 --> 00:43:12.620
from their parents, because
they're so busy working.

00:43:12.620 --> 00:43:15.742
-What's our world going to be
in the future, our generation?

00:43:15.742 --> 00:43:17.200
What are we going
to do, how are we

00:43:17.200 --> 00:43:19.060
going to step up to the plate?

00:43:19.060 --> 00:43:21.730
-We have the opportunity to
help other human beings out,

00:43:21.730 --> 00:43:25.010
and I kind of feel it's
our responsibility to.

00:43:25.010 --> 00:43:26.815
-So I'll need to be
more giving and I'll

00:43:26.815 --> 00:43:30.200
need to be disciplined to
know what should be going on.

00:43:30.200 --> 00:43:31.820
-Sometimes I feel
like I need there

00:43:31.820 --> 00:43:34.610
to be an adult for me to be
able to talk about it, you know?

00:43:34.610 --> 00:43:37.550
About sex and drugs
and-- I fear it

00:43:37.550 --> 00:43:38.800
because I don't know about it.

00:43:41.830 --> 00:43:43.480
-Don't be afraid to take risks.

00:43:43.480 --> 00:43:45.510
-It all starts with
one person, really.

00:43:45.510 --> 00:43:47.360
One person can change the world.

00:43:50.630 --> 00:43:51.780
-If you respect me--

00:43:51.780 --> 00:43:52.690
-I will hear you.

00:43:52.690 --> 00:43:53.930
-If you listen to me--

00:43:53.930 --> 00:43:55.070
-I will feel understood.

00:43:55.070 --> 00:43:56.090
-If you understand me--

00:43:56.090 --> 00:43:57.750
-I will feel appreciated.

00:43:57.750 --> 00:43:59.257
-If you appreciate me--

00:43:59.257 --> 00:44:00.340
-I will know your support.

00:44:00.340 --> 00:44:01.520
-If you support me--

00:44:01.520 --> 00:44:02.890
-As I try new things--

00:44:02.890 --> 00:44:04.530
-I will become responsible.

00:44:04.530 --> 00:44:05.920
-When I am responsible--

00:44:05.920 --> 00:44:07.610
-I will grow to be independent.

00:44:07.610 --> 00:44:08.760
-In my independence--

00:44:08.760 --> 00:44:12.235
-I will respect you and
love you all of my life.

00:44:21.954 --> 00:44:24.940
[END PLAYBACK]

00:44:24.940 --> 00:44:28.630
FREDERICK MARX: To get us there,
all that's needed, really,

00:44:28.630 --> 00:44:31.770
are community-based,
culturally-tailored rites

00:44:31.770 --> 00:44:32.865
of passage and mentorship.

00:44:35.670 --> 00:44:41.580
And the promise that's before us
is that if we do that, then all

00:44:41.580 --> 00:44:44.640
our young people-- in
their independence--

00:44:44.640 --> 00:44:49.420
are going to love us and honor
us for the rest of their lives.

00:44:49.420 --> 00:44:51.220
So thank you, appreciate it.

00:44:55.790 --> 00:45:00.730
AUDIENCE: You talked about--
in the film-- regionally,

00:45:00.730 --> 00:45:03.870
culturally specific
rites of passage.

00:45:03.870 --> 00:45:06.110
I was involved in a summer
mathematics program--

00:45:06.110 --> 00:45:07.555
and I know maybe
other people here

00:45:07.555 --> 00:45:09.660
have been involved in the
first robotics program--

00:45:09.660 --> 00:45:14.300
and there was those sorts of
experiences for people who

00:45:14.300 --> 00:45:16.566
were mathematically-inclined
or technically-inclined,

00:45:16.566 --> 00:45:18.440
but that was a very
specific rite of passage.

00:45:18.440 --> 00:45:20.740
It wouldn't work for
lots and lots of people,

00:45:20.740 --> 00:45:23.120
but it really worked
for those people.

00:45:23.120 --> 00:45:26.320
But what about those
individually specific rites

00:45:26.320 --> 00:45:28.430
of passage?

00:45:28.430 --> 00:45:31.160
FREDERICK MARX: Well,
that's absolutely-- I'm not

00:45:31.160 --> 00:45:32.160
sure what you're asking.

00:45:32.160 --> 00:45:34.140
It's wonderful and
it's appropriate

00:45:34.140 --> 00:45:36.270
and that was right for
you and that's great.

00:45:36.270 --> 00:45:37.890
But it sounds like
you weren't alone,

00:45:37.890 --> 00:45:41.120
though, you had a
cohort with you.

00:45:41.120 --> 00:45:42.460
All the better.

00:45:42.460 --> 00:45:46.200
Ideally it's never
an isolated act.

00:45:46.200 --> 00:45:50.810
We might be isolated
for parts of the ordeal,

00:45:50.810 --> 00:45:53.910
but we always have
to begin and end

00:45:53.910 --> 00:45:57.670
in integration with community.

00:45:57.670 --> 00:46:01.280
The more that you can experience
an ordeal in conjunction

00:46:01.280 --> 00:46:04.380
and relationship with
others, the deeper you'll

00:46:04.380 --> 00:46:06.240
understand your
interconnectedness

00:46:06.240 --> 00:46:09.470
and the deeper those bonds
of love will be driven.

00:46:09.470 --> 00:46:13.820
So fantastic, great.

00:46:13.820 --> 00:46:19.730
AUDIENCE: My question is
basically around balancing

00:46:19.730 --> 00:46:24.860
between the importance of the
individual and the community.

00:46:24.860 --> 00:46:29.410
I myself was raised Catholic
and I went through confirmation,

00:46:29.410 --> 00:46:35.540
and it wasn't a very valuable
experience in my mind.

00:46:35.540 --> 00:46:40.390
So what I'm wondering
is how do you

00:46:40.390 --> 00:46:45.650
ensure that these rites of
passage-- in some ways--

00:46:45.650 --> 00:46:49.640
don't become codified
to meaninglessness

00:46:49.640 --> 00:46:51.640
when everyone
around you is going

00:46:51.640 --> 00:46:53.470
through the same
rite of passage?

00:46:53.470 --> 00:46:55.350
Such that it doesn't
mean anything

00:46:55.350 --> 00:46:57.931
to you because everyone else
is doing the same thing.

00:46:57.931 --> 00:46:59.680
FREDERICK MARX: Well
again, that gets back

00:46:59.680 --> 00:47:02.930
to the definition of the
efficacy of a rite of passage.

00:47:02.930 --> 00:47:06.000
We need to hear the testimony
from the young people

00:47:06.000 --> 00:47:07.030
themselves.

00:47:07.030 --> 00:47:10.350
They have to be the ones to say
I'm the proof of the pudding,

00:47:10.350 --> 00:47:11.330
this worked.

00:47:11.330 --> 00:47:14.880
And if it didn't, then we need
to offer them something else.

00:47:14.880 --> 00:47:16.980
But that's the function
of elders in society,

00:47:16.980 --> 00:47:22.707
too, because they're constantly
alert to the responses

00:47:22.707 --> 00:47:24.790
that the young people are
giving and they can see,

00:47:24.790 --> 00:47:28.460
well, Joey's not really
responding to this.

00:47:28.460 --> 00:47:29.370
What does he need?

00:47:29.370 --> 00:47:32.560
What do we need to
do with and for him

00:47:32.560 --> 00:47:35.240
that's going to give
him a deeper experience?

00:47:35.240 --> 00:47:37.830
So that's essential.

00:47:37.830 --> 00:47:40.840
And it's interesting, too-- I'll
use your question to spring off

00:47:40.840 --> 00:47:44.110
a little bit-- it's both and.

00:47:44.110 --> 00:47:46.120
Meaning if you're
Catholic, great.

00:47:46.120 --> 00:47:48.700
Ideally we have
Catholic confirmation

00:47:48.700 --> 00:47:51.470
as rites of passage that
are potent, that actually

00:47:51.470 --> 00:47:54.430
do what they're designed to do,
to grow you into that man you

00:47:54.430 --> 00:47:55.620
want to become.

00:47:55.620 --> 00:47:57.840
But we also have to
make room for Catholics

00:47:57.840 --> 00:48:02.240
like yourself who say, I don't
want that for whatever reason.

00:48:02.240 --> 00:48:04.860
We have to respect that,
too, and offer them

00:48:04.860 --> 00:48:07.970
something else that will
also give them an opportunity

00:48:07.970 --> 00:48:10.110
to discover their
gifts, but maybe

00:48:10.110 --> 00:48:13.202
outside of that
Catholic context.

00:48:13.202 --> 00:48:15.660
AUDIENCE: I know there was a
slide that mentioned the three

00:48:15.660 --> 00:48:19.180
phases of the rite of passage.

00:48:19.180 --> 00:48:21.680
Is there any sort
of research more

00:48:21.680 --> 00:48:25.800
