00:54:16.610 --> 00:54:20.715
to actually help their teens
to go through that process?

00:54:20.715 --> 00:54:22.090
FREDERICK MARX:
Yeah, absolutely.

00:54:22.090 --> 00:54:24.340
Well in fact, the
parents curriculum,

00:54:24.340 --> 00:54:28.570
it starts with them at
about sixth grade-- so 12,

00:54:28.570 --> 00:54:29.740
13 years old.

00:54:29.740 --> 00:54:32.260
And for every year
for six years,

00:54:32.260 --> 00:54:36.120
we have a whole set of different
ideas for things we can do.

00:54:36.120 --> 00:54:38.470
So one example that
comes right to my mind--

00:54:38.470 --> 00:54:42.450
because I faced this
with my niece recently--

00:54:42.450 --> 00:54:45.360
she just turned 16
in January and we

00:54:45.360 --> 00:54:48.090
were trying to get
her-- on her own--

00:54:48.090 --> 00:54:50.610
to take a trip out to see us.

00:54:50.610 --> 00:54:54.660
She lives with my sister
right outside New York City.

00:54:54.660 --> 00:54:57.860
And that's one of the things
that is in this program,

00:54:57.860 --> 00:55:01.450
it's designing trips
for young people

00:55:01.450 --> 00:55:05.590
to experience the
world on their own.

00:55:05.590 --> 00:55:08.860
It can start with day
trips, just even walking

00:55:08.860 --> 00:55:11.470
around their community
and seeing it, perhaps,

00:55:11.470 --> 00:55:14.300
for the first time with
new eyes in different ways.

00:55:14.300 --> 00:55:16.320
And building up to
things like that,

00:55:16.320 --> 00:55:18.400
where you go
cross-country on your own,

00:55:18.400 --> 00:55:21.180
the first time ever on
a plane by yourself,

00:55:21.180 --> 00:55:23.430
and get yourself
to someplace else.

00:55:23.430 --> 00:55:26.530
And then to also
