00:55:39.360 --> 00:55:41.010
to be a mentor for
the first time.

00:55:41.010 --> 00:55:41.450
FREDERICK MARX: Yay.

00:55:41.450 --> 00:55:43.616
AUDIENCE: So I came more
for a personal perspective.

00:55:43.616 --> 00:55:46.010
And I was wondering if you
had any suggestions or advice

00:55:46.010 --> 00:55:49.030
for how-- as a mentor
on a limited timeframe--

00:55:49.030 --> 00:55:51.360
I can actually help this
transition along given

00:55:51.360 --> 00:55:54.240
that I can't create or implement
a specific rite of passage.

00:55:54.240 --> 00:55:55.990
FREDERICK MARX: Well,
I'll try to give you

00:55:55.990 --> 00:56:01.180
a crash course in what I know of
mentorship in a minute or less.

00:56:01.180 --> 00:56:04.570
First of all, you've
got to be accountable

00:56:04.570 --> 00:56:05.890
to that young person.

00:56:05.890 --> 00:56:08.709
So whatever time you set to
meet them, you've got to do it.

00:56:08.709 --> 00:56:10.625
And if you don't, then
you have to renegotiate

00:56:10.625 --> 00:56:12.530
and be accountable for it.

00:56:12.530 --> 00:56:15.140
Regularity is key, as you
probably already know.

00:56:15.140 --> 00:56:19.140
Ideally once a week or
more for a couple hours.

00:56:19.140 --> 00:56:24.180
I use the 80-20 ratio, listening
to them 80% of the time

00:56:24.180 --> 00:56:26.070
and speaking 20%.

00:56:26.070 --> 00:56:28.880
So many of us think,
OK, I'm a mentor now,

00:56:28.880 --> 00:56:30.639
I've got to share
all my life wisdom

00:56:30.639 --> 00:56:32.180
and I'm going to
tell you what to do.

00:56:32.180 --> 00:56:35.530
No, it's about listening to
them and deeply understanding

00:56:35.530 --> 00:56:39.110
where they're at,
and going from there.

00:56:39.110 --> 00:56:42.010
Just in that listening,
we bless them

00:56:42.010 --> 00:56:45.110
through our kind and
compassionate attention.

00:56:45.110 --> 00:56:48.300
That is one of the greatest
gifts a mentor can bring.

00:56:48.300 --> 00:56:51.510
So that's some of it.

00:56:51.510 --> 00:56:54.590
I hope that's helpful.

00:56:54.590 --> 00:56:55.930
And bless you for doing that.

00:56:55.930 --> 00:56:58.590
In fact, that's my final
question to all of you.

00:56:58.590 --> 00:57:03.470
How many of you are
mentoring and how many of you

00:57:03.470 --> 00:57:05.220
are being mentored?

00:57:05.220 --> 00:57:09.280
Because that's how we reform,
again, the torn fabric

00:57:09.280 --> 00:57:13.200
of community and that's how
we create links through time.

00:57:13.200 --> 00:57:16.450
That's how generational
links happen.

00:57:16.450 --> 00:57:19.390
So as I told you, I'm
turning 60 in a few weeks.

00:57:19.390 --> 00:57:22.820
Believe me, I still have
mentors who I can turn to,

00:57:22.820 --> 00:57:24.780
to give me all kinds of
advice when I need it

00:57:24.780 --> 00:57:27.180
and also to kick my
ass when I need it.

00:57:27.180 --> 00:57:29.120
And I sure as heck
am also mentoring

00:57:29.120 --> 00:57:30.680
a number of young people.

00:57:30.680 --> 00:57:33.590
And sometimes not young--
my age or even older--

00:57:33.590 --> 00:57:36.640
but also offering
those that mentorship.

00:57:36.640 --> 00:57:40.430
So I really invite you to do
that, because it's essential.

00:57:40.430 --> 00:57:42.340
And here's another one for you.

00:57:42.340 --> 00:57:45.050
If you're not growing as
much as that young person,

00:57:45.050 --> 00:57:46.570
something's wrong.

00:57:46.570 --> 00:57:48.780
Something is
fundamentally wrong,

00:57:48.780 --> 00:57:53.010
because you need to be growing
yourself in the process.

00:57:53.010 --> 00:57:56.890
And if you're not, then you
really need to retool it.

00:57:56.890 --> 00:57:58.950
Thank you all again.

